outputs.description: RKLA 3:  By 2015, the education system ensures increased access to an affordable and quality pre-school education system in twelvepriority districts
4.2. By 2015, public policy and budgeting supports child-friendly social sector development.
4.1. By 2015, disaggregated data on the wellbeing of children is available in a timely manner and used to inform policy and itsimplementation
By 2015, the Ministry of Education implements in eight priority districts specific interventions to increase attendance andenrolment in grades 7-9
By 2015, 825 secondary schools deliver HIV/AIDS and other LSBE classes in grades 7-9
By 2015, National government, local authorities, school children and communities in selected districts have strengthened theircapacity to plan, prepare for and respond to emergencies
4.3. Strong Partnership for Children's rights is developed with mass media, national and local government, civil society and otherdevelopment partners
1. 5. By 2015, outreach services and STI/HIV voluntary counselling, testing and treatment for MARA are provided in all 21 YFHSclinics nationwide.
By 2015, in 65 per cent of schools in eight priority districts, all students use safe water and improved gender-sensitivefacilities

1. 4. By 2015, in all reproductive health centres and maternity houses of 18 districts, pregnant women of at risk profile receiveVCT and if HIV positive, receive ARV in accordance with PMTCT protocol  and HIV positive children have access to ARV prevention,treatment and social services.
6.1. Effective management of supply and procurement
By 2015, improved policies, practices and services to effectively prevent and respond to unnecessary institutionalization ofchildren (especially children under three and children with disabilities)
By 2015, the family substitute care services function according to the quality standards set out in the national policy.
By 2015, children in contact with the law are treated more in compliance with international norms and standards on justice forchildren

1. 2. By 2015, the Ministry of Health provides all women as well as newborn infants in all maternal facilities of 8 prioritydistricts with quality antenatal and essential obstetric and newborn care services in accordance with international standards.
1. 3. By 2015, at least 80% of households in 8 priority districts practice interventions on child survival, care and nutrition.
1.1. By 2015, the Ministry of Health increases allocation of resources to maternal and child survival/nutrition strategies withinits budgetary frameworks, including SWAp.
